(1) Broome, to Sullivan, to Clark Streets. (Before Reconstruction). March 22, 1920.
(2) Same. (After Reconstruction).
September 18, 1921.

Broome Street, west from Sullivan Street, showing the bend in Broome Street at the southern end of Clark Street. The buildings in the immediate foreground are directly in the path of Sixth Avenue extension, and are about to be demolished. The west side of Clark Street will form part of the west side of Sixth Avenue. The white building at the west corner of Clark Street is Public School No. 38.

1926.

Clark Street, north from Broome to Spring Streets, showing the Butterick Building at the corner of Spring and MacDougal Streets. Between 6 and 16 Clark Street, the loft buildings on the east side; is a playground for the children of Public School No. 38, No. 1-19, on the west side. In 1928 Clark Street will be absorbed by the extension of Sixth Avenue; the entire east side will be demolished, while the west side will become part of the west side of Sixth Avenue.

1926.
Sullivan Street, south from and including Broome Street. 1926.

55, 57, 59, 61, 63-67 Sullivan Street, at and adjoining the N.E. corner of Broome Street, seen from Sixth Avenue Extension, the former west side of Sullivan Street, during the early stages of subway construction. Nos. 57 and 59 Sullivan Street, adjoining the corner, are frame houses faced with brick.
October 19, 1928.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)
The same, with clearing at 55 Sullivan Street, the identical scene three and a half years later, showing the N.E. corner of Sixth Avenue in the left foreground. The new subway is completed, but will not be opened till September 10 of the year of this view. The corner building at Sullivan and Broome Streets has been demolished, exposing the frame south side of No. 57 Sullivan Street.
March 19, 1932.

P. L. Sperr.

Sixth Avenue (left), east side, and Sullivan Street (right), east side, north from Broome Street. The two houses at the N.E. corner of Sullivan and Broome Streets have been demolished, leaving exposed the frame side of 59 Sullivan Street adjoining the vacant corner.
March 19, 1932.

P. L. Sperr.
title: Manhattan : 6th Avenue - Broome Street

text:
Sixth Ave. (Extension), west side, south from, but not including Broome, to and including Watts Streets, showing (at the extreme right) a portion of the Underwriters Salvage Co. 6-story building, at the S.W. corner of Broome Street. The 3-story house, in the center of the view, is a frame building, and bears the No. 46 Watts Street, and is at the N.W. corner.

June 7, 1933.

P. L. Sperr.
title: Manhattan : 6th Avenue - w.s. - South - Broome Street

text:
Sixth Avenue, west side, from Broome to Dominick Streets, showing P. S. No. 38. Prior to the extension of 6th Avenue this frontage was a part of Clark Street. This street, only 2 blocks long was completely obliterated. Broome Street is on the left and the view there extends to Varick Street. In the foreground is Sullivan Street separated from the new 6th Avenue by a triangular plot.

June 7, 1933
Views 1,2

P. L. Sperr

text:
(1)
Sullivan Street, east side, from Broome to Spring Streets, seen from Sixth Avenue at Spring Street. South of Broome Street, Sullivan Street has been absorbed by Sixth Avenue.
Nos. 57, 59 Sullivan Street, adjoining the vacant N.E. corner of Broome Street, are frame houses, faced with brick, and so are 85, 87 Sullivan Street, the two little houses adjoining the five-story tenement house at the S.E. corner of Spring Street. No. 87 has an attic with dormer windows.
1932.

J. Clarence Davies Collection, Museum of the City of New York.

(2)
A view of both sides of Sullivan Street, northward.

January 30, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.
